[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] This feature is not Baseline because it does not work in some of the most widely-used browsers.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] The **Cooperative Scheduling of Background Tasks API** (also referred to as the Background Tasks API or the `requestIdleCallback()` API) provides the ability to queue tasks to be executed automatically by the user agent when it determines that there is free time to do so.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] The main thread of a Web browser is centered around its event loop.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] This code draws any pending updates to the `Document` currently being displayed, runs any JavaScript code the page needs to run, accepts events from input devices, and dispatches those events to the elements that should receive them.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] In addition, the event loop handles interactions with the operating system, updates to the browser's own user interface, and so forth.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] It's an extremely busy chunk of code, and your main JavaScript code may run right inside this thread along with all of this.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Certainly most if not all code that is capable of making changes to the DOM is running in the main thread, since it's common for user interface changes to only be available to the main thread.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Because event handling and screen updates are two of the most obvious ways users notice performance issues, it's important for your code to be a good citizen of the Web and help to prevent stalls in the execution of the event loop.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] In the past, there's been no way to do this reliably other than by writing code that's as efficient as possible and by offloading as much work as possible to workers.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] `Window.requestIdleCallback()` makes it possible to become actively engaged in helping to ensure that the browser's event loop runs smoothly, by allowing the browser to tell your code how much time it can safely use without causing the system to lag.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] If you stay within the limit given, you can make the user's experience much better.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Because idle callbacks are intended to give your code a way to cooperate with the event loop to ensure that the system is utilized to its full potential without over-tasking it, resulting in lag or other performance problems, you should be thoughtful about how you go about using them.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] An object of this type is passed to the idle callback to provide an estimate of how long the idle period is expected to last, as well as whether or not the callback is running because its timeout period has expired.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] The `Window` interface is also augmented by this API to offer the new `requestIdleCallback()` and `cancelIdleCallback()` methods.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] In this example, we'll take a look at how you can use `requestIdleCallback()` to run time-consuming, low-priority tasks during time the browser would otherwise be idle.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] In addition, this example demonstrates how to schedule updates to the document content using `requestAnimationFrame()`.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Below you'll find only the HTML and JavaScript for this example.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] The CSS is not shown, since it's not particularly crucial to understanding this functionality.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] In order to be oriented about what we're trying to accomplish, let's have a look at the HTML.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] This establishes a box (`id="container"`) that's used to present the progress of an operation (because you never know how long decoding "quantum filament tachyon emissions" will take, after all) as well as a second main box (`id="logBox"`), which is used to display textual output.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] The progress box uses a `<progress>` element to show the progress, along with a label with sections that are changed to present numeric information about the progress.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] In addition, there's a "Start" button (creatively given the ID "startButton"), which the user will use to start the data processing.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Now that the document structure is defined, construct the JavaScript code that will do the work.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] The goal: to be able to add requests to call functions to a queue, with an idle callback that runs those functions whenever the system is idle for long enough a time to make progress.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Next we have variables which reference the DOM elements we need to interact with.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Next, let's look at the way we manage the tasks that need to be performed.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] We're going to do this by creating a FIFO queue of tasks, which we'll run as time allows during the idle callback period.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] First, we need a function that enqueues tasks for future execution.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Next, we check to see if we already have an idle callback created; if `taskHandle` is 0, we know there isn't an idle callback yet, so we call `requestIdleCallback()` to create one.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] It's configured to call a function called `runTaskQueue()`, which we'll look at shortly, and with a `timeout` of 1 second, so that it will be run at least once per second even if there isn't any actual idle time available.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Our idle callback handler, `runTaskQueue()`, gets called when the browser determines there's enough idle time available to let us do some work or our timeout of one second expires.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] This function's job is to run our enqueued tasks.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] `runTaskQueue()`'s core is a loop which continues as long as there's time left (as determined by checking `deadline.timeRemaining`) to be sure it's more than 0 or if the timeout limit was reached (`deadline.didTimeout` is true), and as long as there are tasks in the task list.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] We increment `currentTaskNumber` to track how many tasks we've executed.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] We call the task's handler, `task.handler`, passing into it the task's data object (`task.data`).
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] We call a function, `scheduleStatusRefresh()`, to handle scheduling a screen update to reflect changes to our progress.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] When time runs out, if there are still tasks left in the list, we call `requestIdleCallback()` again so that we can continue to process the tasks the next time there's idle time available.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] If the queue is empty, we set taskHandle to 0 to indicate that we don't have a callback scheduled.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] That way, we'll know to request a callback next time `enqueueTask()` is called.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] One thing we want to be able to do is update our document with log output and progress information.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] However, you can't safely change the DOM from within an idle callback.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Instead, we'll use `requestAnimationFrame()` to ask the browser to call us when it's safe to update the display.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] DOM changes are scheduled by calling the `scheduleStatusRefresh()` function.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] It checks to see if we've already scheduled a display refresh by checking the value of `statusRefreshScheduled`.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] If it's `false`, we call `requestAnimationFrame()` to schedule a refresh, providing the `updateDisplay()` function to be called to handle that work.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] The `updateDisplay()` function is responsible for drawing the contents of the progress box and the log.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] It's called by the browser when the DOM is in a safe condition for us to apply changes during the process of rendering the next frame.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] First, `scrolledToEnd` is set to `true` if the text in the log is scrolled to the bottom; otherwise it's set to `false`.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] We'll use that to determine if we should update the scroll position to ensure that the log stays at the end when we're done adding content to it.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Next, we update the progress and status information if any tasks have been enqueued.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] We do the same thing with the number of tasks processed so far; if `progressBarElem.value` is different from the task number currently being processed (`currentTaskNumber`), then we update the displayed value of the currently-being-processed task and the current value of the progress bar.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Then, if there's text waiting to be added to the log (that is, if `logFragment` isn't `null`), we append it to the log element using `Element.appendChild()` and set `logFragment` to `null` so we don't add it again.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] If the log was scrolled to the end when we started, we make sure it still is.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Then we set `statusRefreshScheduled` to `false` to indicate that we've handled the refresh and that it's safe to request a new one.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] The `log()` function adds the specified text to the log.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Since we don't know at the time `log()` is called whether or not it's safe to immediately touch the DOM, we will cache the log text until it's safe to update.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Above, in the code for `updateDisplay()`, you can find the code that actually adds the logged text to the log element when the animation frame is being updated.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] First, we create a `DocumentFragment` object named `logFragment` if one doesn't currently exist.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] This element is a pseudo-DOM into which we can insert elements without immediately changing the main DOM itself.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] We then create a new `<div>` element and set its contents to match the input `text`.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Then we append the new element to the end of the pseudo-DOM in `logFragment`.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] `logFragment` will accumulate log entries until the next time `updateDisplay()` is called, once the DOM is ready for the changes.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Now that we've got the task management and display maintenance code done, we can actually start setting up code to run tasks that get work done.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] The function we'll be using as our task handler—that is, the function that will be used as the value of the task object's `handler` property—is `logTaskHandler()`.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] It's a simple function that outputs a bunch of stuff to the log for each task.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] In your own application, you'd replace this code with whatever task it is you wish to perform during idle time.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Just remember that anything you want to do that changes the DOM needs to be handled through `requestAnimationFrame()`.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Everything is triggered when the user clicks the Start button, which causes the `decodeTechnoStuff()` function to be called.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] `decodeTechnoStuff()` starts by zeroing the values of totalTaskCount (the number of tasks added to the queue so far) and currentTaskNumber (the task currently being run), and then calls `updateDisplay()` to reset the display to its "nothing's happened yet" state.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] This example will create a random number of tasks (between 100 and 200 of them).
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] To do so, we use the `getRandomIntInclusive()` function that's provided as an example in the documentation for `Math.random()` to get the number of tasks to create.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Then we start a loop to create the actual tasks.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Each task is then enqueued by calling `enqueueTask()`, passing in `logTaskHandler()` as the handler function and the `taskData` object as the object to pass into the function when it's called.
[src:requestidlecallback/background-tasks-api] Below is the actual functioning result of the code above.
