[src:requestidlecallback/cancelidlecallback] The **`window.cancelIdleCallback()`** method cancels a callback previously scheduled with `window.requestIdleCallback()`.
[src:requestidlecallback/cancelidlecallback] The ID value returned by `window.requestIdleCallback()` when the callback was established.
[src:requestidlecallback/cancelidlecallback] See our complete example in the article Cooperative Scheduling of Background Tasks API.
[src:requestidlecallback/cooperative-multitasking] In this scheme, the process scheduler of an operating system is known as a **cooperative scheduler** whose role is limited to starting the processes and letting them return control back to it voluntarily.
[src:requestidlecallback/cooperative-multitasking] This is related to the asynchronous programming approach.
[src:requestidlecallback/cooperative-multitasking] Although it is rarely used as the primary scheduling mechanism in modern operating systems, it is widely used in memory-constrained embedded systems and in specific applications such as CICS or the JES2 subsystem.
[src:requestidlecallback/cooperative-multitasking] Cooperative multitasking was the primary scheduling scheme for 16-bit applications employed by Microsoft Windows before Windows 95 and Windows NT, and by the classic Mac OS.
[src:requestidlecallback/cooperative-multitasking] Windows 9x used non-preemptive multitasking for 16-bit legacy applications, and the PowerPC Versions of Mac OS X prior to Leopard used it for classic applications.
[src:requestidlecallback/cooperative-multitasking] NetWare, which is a network-oriented operating system, used cooperative multitasking up to NetWare 6.5.
[src:requestidlecallback/cooperative-multitasking] Cooperative multitasking is still used on RISC OS systems.
[src:requestidlecallback/cooperative-multitasking] Cooperative multitasking is similar to async/await in languages, such as JavaScript or Python, that feature a single-threaded event-loop in their runtime.
[src:requestidlecallback/cooperative-multitasking] This contrasts with cooperative multitasking in that await cannot be invoked from a non-async function, but only an async function, which is a kind of coroutine.
[src:requestidlecallback/cooperative-multitasking] Cooperative multitasking allows much simpler implementation of applications because their execution is never unexpectedly interrupted by the process scheduler; for example, various functions inside the application do not need to be reentrant.
[src:requestidlecallback/cooperative-multitasking] As a cooperatively multitasked system relies on each process regularly giving up time to other processes on the system, one poorly designed program can consume all of the CPU time for itself, either by performing extensive calculations or by busy waiting; both would cause the whole system to hang.
[src:requestidlecallback/cooperative-multitasking] In a server environment, this is a hazard that is often considered to make the entire environment unacceptably fragile, though as noted above, cooperative multitasking has been used frequently in server environments, including NetWare and CICS.
[src:requestidlecallback/cooperative-multitasking] In contrast, preemptive multitasking interrupts applications and gives control to other processes outside the application's control.
[src:requestidlecallback/cooperative-multitasking] The potential for system hang can be alleviated by using a watchdog timer, often implemented in hardware; this typically invokes a hardware reset.
[src:requestidlecallback/idle-cpu] Every program or task that runs on a computer system occupies a certain amount of processing time on the CPU.
[src:requestidlecallback/idle-cpu] If the CPU has completed all tasks it is idle.
[src:requestidlecallback/idle-cpu] Modern processors use idle time to save power.
[src:requestidlecallback/idle-cpu] Common methods are reducing the clock speed along with the CPU voltage and sending parts of the processor into a sleep state.
[src:requestidlecallback/idle-cpu] On processors that have a halt instruction that stops the CPU until an interrupt occurs, such as x86's HLT instruction, it may save significant amounts of power and heat if the idle task consists of a loop which repeatedly executes that instruction.
[src:requestidlecallback/idle-cpu] Many operating systems, for example Windows, Linux, and macOS will run an **idle task**, which is a special task loaded by the OS scheduler on a CPU when there is nothing for the CPU to do.
[src:requestidlecallback/idle-cpu] The idle task can be hard-coded into the scheduler, or it can be implemented as a separate task with the lowest possible priority.
[src:requestidlecallback/idle-cpu] An advantage of the latter approach is that programs monitoring the system status can see the idle task along with all other tasks; an example is Windows NT's System Idle Process.
[src:requestidlecallback/idle-cpu] Some programs are designed to appear to make use of CPU idle time, meaning that they run at a low priority (but slightly higher than idle priority) so as not to impact programs that run at normal priority.
[src:requestidlecallback/idle-cpu] This allows non-crucial background programs to only run when it would not affect the performance of other applications.
[src:requestidlecallback/idledeadline] The `IdleDeadline` interface is used as the data type of the input parameter to idle callbacks established by calling `Window.requestIdleCallback()`.
[src:requestidlecallback/idledeadline] It offers a method, `timeRemaining()`, which lets you determine how much longer the user agent estimates it will remain idle and a property, `didTimeout`, which lets you determine if your callback is executing because its timeout duration expired.
[src:requestidlecallback/idledeadline] To learn more about how request callbacks work, see Collaborative Scheduling of Background Tasks.
[src:requestidlecallback/idledeadline] A Boolean whose value is `true` if the callback is being executed because the timeout specified when the idle callback was installed has expired.
[src:requestidlecallback/idledeadline] Returns a `DOMHighResTimeStamp`, which is a floating-point value providing an estimate of the number of milliseconds remaining in the current idle period.
[src:requestidlecallback/idledeadline] If the idle period is over, the value is 0.
[src:requestidlecallback/idledeadline] Your callback can call this repeatedly to see if there's enough time left to do more work before returning.
[src:requestidlecallback/requestidlecallback] The **`window.requestIdleCallback()`** method queues a function to be called during a browser's idle periods.
[src:requestidlecallback/requestidlecallback] This enables developers to perform background and low priority work on the main thread, without impacting latency-critical events such as animation and input response.
[src:requestidlecallback/requestidlecallback] Functions are generally called in first-in-first-out order; however, callbacks which have a `timeout` specified may be called out-of-order if necessary in order to run them before the timeout elapses.
[src:requestidlecallback/requestidlecallback] You can call `requestIdleCallback()` within an idle callback function to schedule another callback to take place no sooner than the next pass through the event loop.
[src:requestidlecallback/requestidlecallback] A reference to a function that should be called in the near future, when the event loop is idle.
[src:requestidlecallback/requestidlecallback] The callback function is passed an `IdleDeadline` object describing the amount of time available and whether or not the callback has been run because the timeout period expired.
[src:requestidlecallback/requestidlecallback] Contains optional configuration parameters.
[src:requestidlecallback/requestidlecallback] If the number of milliseconds represented by this parameter has elapsed and the callback has not already been called, then a task to execute the callback is queued in the event loop (even if doing so risks causing a negative performance impact).
[src:requestidlecallback/requestidlecallback] `timeout` must be a positive value or it is ignored.
[src:requestidlecallback/requestidlecallback] An ID which can be used to cancel the callback by passing it into the `window.cancelIdleCallback()` method.
